  "opinion": "Stereotype threat in STEM isn't just a theoretical buzzword—it's something I've seen play out in my own life and around me. Growing up in Chicago with parents who had only primary school and vocational training, I never really had the academic push to go beyond high school. But when I started working as an electrician, I saw how students from similar backgrounds often feel the weight of stereotypes about being 'not smart enough' for science fields. That fear isn't just about failing—it's about the anxiety that makes you doubt your own abilities before even starting. I've noticed it in my own kids, who sometimes avoid math problems because they think they're 'not the type' for it. Addressing stereotype threat isn't about fixing people—it's about changing the environment so that students don't have to carry that burden of self-doubt. In my community, we could do better by creating mentorship programs that connect students with working professionals like me, showing them that STEM isn't just for those with fancy degrees. It’s about making sure kids from all backgrounds feel they belong, not just that they're 'good enough.' And honestly, given my own struggles with depression and the stress of being someone who didn't follow the traditional academic path, I think we need to be more compassionate about how we frame success in these fields. The answer isn't just more programs—it's about listening and adapting to what actually works for real people, not just the ones who fit the mold.",
